RootCauseAnalysis - INFO -     Result: {'result': 'Based on my analysis of the trace data, I can now provide a comprehensive assessment of the discrepancy between client and server span durations for calls from checkoutservice to cartservice.\n\nFrom the trace_analysis_tool results, I can see that there are significant latency anomalies:\n- `checkoutservice → cartservice EmptyCart`: Normal avg 2409.5ms → Anomaly avg 61440.5ms (25.5x increase)\n- `checkoutservice → cartservice GetCart`: Normal avg 2495.9ms → Anomaly avg 29882.5ms (12x increase)\n- `checkoutservice internal CartService calls`: Also showing 4-5x latency increases\n\nHowever, when I examine the raw traces from the search results, I notice a critical issue: **the returned traces only show frontend → cartservice calls, not checkoutservice → cartservice calls**. This suggests that during the anomaly period (2025-06-27T00:10:17Z to 2025-06-27T00:24:17Z), there may be missing trace data specifically for checkoutservice client spans calling cartservice.\n\nLooking at the trace timestamps in the search results, all the returned spans are from "2025-06-26 16:01:xx" which appears to be outside the anomaly time window. This indicates that either:\n1. The checkoutservice pods were not generating client spans during the anomaly period (suggesting they were down or not processing requests)\n2. There\'s a data collection issue\n3. The actual root cause is that checkoutservice couldn\'t reach cartservice at all\n\nThe trace_analysis_tool shows checkoutservice experiencing high latency when calling cartservice, but the raw trace search doesn\'t return actual checkoutservice client spans during the anomaly period. This pattern suggests that checkoutservice was attempting to call cartservice but either:\n- The requests never reached cartservice (network issue)\n- Cartservice was unavailable (pod crash)\n- The connection was refused immediately\n\nGiven that the trace_analysis_tool shows both client-side (checkoutservice)